{{Expand German|Die Hussitenpredigt|date=July 2018}}
{{Infobox artwork|title=The Hussite Sermon|image=Hussitenpredigt.jpg|artist=Carl Friedrich Lessing|medium=oil on canvas|height_metric=223|width_metric=293 cm|museum=Alte Nationalgalerie|city=Berlin}}
'''''The Hussite Sermon''''' (German - ''Die Hussitenpredigt'') is a painting by the [[Düsseldorf]]-based painter [[Carl Friedrich Lessing]], showing an open-air sermon being delivered by a [[Hussite]] preacher in the 15th century. It is now in the [[Alte Nationalgalerie]] in Berlin.

In 1834 [[Frederick William IV|Crown Prince Frederick William of Prussia]] saw an oil sketch on the subject by Lessing in 1834 and commissioned him between 1835 and 1836 to produce a full-scale version. The mainly-Catholic Rhineland had recently been annexed to the Protestant-dominated [[Kingdom of Prussia]] by the [[Congress of Vienna]] and so the work was seen as a piece of anti-Catholic propaganda for the area's Protestant minority. In the context of the Restoration of the German princes to their thrones and the [[Vormärz]], others also saw it as a criticism of the repressiveness of the states and systems put in place by Metternich and the Congress. Middle-class audiences saw it as an expression of opposition to kingly and church authority alike. It was briefly exhibited in Germany and Paris, spreading the reputation of the [[Düsseldorf school of painting]].

